4049 def set_index(self, keys, drop=True, append=False, inplace=False, 

4050 verify_integrity=False): 

4051 """ 

4052 Set the DataFrame index using existing columns. 

4053 

4054 Set the DataFrame index (row labels) using one or more existing 

4055 columns or arrays (of the correct length). The index can replace the 

4056 existing index or expand on it. 

4057 

4058 Parameters 

4059 ---------- 

4060 keys : label or array-like or list of labels/arrays 

4061 This parameter can be either a single column key, a single array of 

4062 the same length as the calling DataFrame, or a list containing an 

4063 arbitrary combination of column keys and arrays. Here, "array" 

4064 encompasses :class:`Series`, :class:`Index` and ``np.ndarray``. 

4065 drop : bool, default True 

4066 Delete columns to be used as the new index. 

4067 append : bool, default False 

4068 Whether to append columns to existing index. 

4069 inplace : bool, default False 

4070 Modify the DataFrame in place (do not create a new object). 

4071 verify_integrity : bool, default False 

4072 Check the new index for duplicates. Otherwise defer the check until 

4073 necessary. Setting to False will improve the performance of this 

4074 method. 

4075 

4076 Returns 

4077 ------- 

4078 DataFrame 

4079 Changed row labels. 

4080 

4081 See Also 

4082 -------- 

4083 DataFrame.reset_index : Opposite of set_index. 

4084 DataFrame.reindex : Change to new indices or expand indices. 

4085 DataFrame.reindex_like : Change to same indices as other DataFrame. 

4086 

4087 Examples 

4088 -------- 

4089 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'month': [1, 4, 7, 10], 

4090 ... 'year': [2012, 2014, 2013, 2014], 

4091 ... 'sale': [55, 40, 84, 31]}) 

4092 >>> df 

4093 month year sale 

4094 0 1 2012 55 

4095 1 4 2014 40 

4096 2 7 2013 84 

4097 3 10 2014 31 

4098 

4099 Set the index to become the 'month' column: 

4100 

4101 >>> df.set_index('month') 

4102 year sale 

4103 month 

4104 1 2012 55 

4105 4 2014 40 

4106 7 2013 84 

4107 10 2014 31 

4108 

4109 Create a MultiIndex using columns 'year' and 'month': 

4110 

4111 >>> df.set_index(['year', 'month']) 

4112 sale 

4113 year month 

4114 2012 1 55 

4115 2014 4 40 

4116 2013 7 84 

4117 2014 10 31 

4118 

4119 Create a MultiIndex using an Index and a column: 

4120 

4121 >>> df.set_index([pd.Index([1, 2, 3, 4]), 'year']) 

4122 month sale 

4123 year 

4124 1 2012 1 55 

4125 2 2014 4 40 

4126 3 2013 7 84 

4127 4 2014 10 31 

4128 

4129 Create a MultiIndex using two Series: 

4130 

4131 >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2, 3, 4]) 

4132 >>> df.set_index([s, s**2]) 

4133 month year sale 

4134 1 1 1 2012 55 

4135 2 4 4 2014 40 

4136 3 9 7 2013 84 

4137 4 16 10 2014 31 

4138 """ 

4139 inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, 'inplace') 

4140 if not isinstance(keys, list): 

4141 keys = [keys] 

4142 

4143 if inplace: 

4144 frame = self 

4145 else: 

4146 frame = self.copy() 

4147 

4148 arrays = [] 

4149 names = [] 

4150 if append: 

4151 names = [x for x in self.index.names] 

4152 if isinstance(self.index, MultiIndex): 

4153 for i in range(self.index.nlevels): 

4154 arrays.append(self.index._get_level_values(i)) 

4155 else: 

4156 arrays.append(self.index) 

4157 

4158 to_remove = [] 

4159 for col in keys: 

4160 if isinstance(col, MultiIndex): 

4161 # append all but the last column so we don't have to modify 

4162 # the end of this loop 

4163 for n in range(col.nlevels - 1): 

4164 arrays.append(col._get_level_values(n)) 

4165 

4166 level = col._get_level_values(col.nlevels - 1) 

4167 names.extend(col.names) 

4168 elif isinstance(col, Series): 

4169 level = col._values 

4170 names.append(col.name) 

4171 elif isinstance(col, Index): 

4172 level = col 

4173 names.append(col.name) 

4174 elif isinstance(col, (list, np.ndarray, Index)): 

4175 level = col 

4176 names.append(None) 

4177 else: 

4178 level = frame[col]._values 

4179 names.append(col) 

4180 if drop: 

4181 to_remove.append(col) 

4182 arrays.append(level) 

4183 

4184 index = ensure_index_from_sequences(arrays, names) 

4185 

4186 if verify_integrity and not index.is_unique: 

4187 duplicates = index[index.duplicated()].unique() 

4188 raise ValueError('Index has duplicate keys: {dup}'.format( 

4189 dup=duplicates)) 

4190 

4191 # use set to handle duplicate column names gracefully in case of drop 

4192 for c in set(to_remove): 

4193 del frame[c] 

4194 

4195 # clear up memory usage 

4196 index._cleanup() 

4197 

4198 frame.index = index 

4199 

4200 if not inplace: 

4201 return frame

4352 def _maybe_casted_values(index, labels=None): 

4353 values = index._values 

4354 if not isinstance(index, (PeriodIndex, DatetimeIndex)): 

4355 if values.dtype == np.object_: 

4356 values = lib.maybe_convert_objects(values) 

4357 

4358 # if we have the labels, extract the values with a mask 

4359 if labels is not None: 

4360 mask = labels == -1 

4361 

4362 # we can have situations where the whole mask is -1, 

4363 # meaning there is nothing found in labels, so make all nan's 

4364 if mask.all(): 

4365 values = np.empty(len(mask)) 

4366 values.fill(np.nan) 

4367 else: 

4368 values = values.take(labels) 

4369 

4370 # TODO(https://github.com/pandas-dev/pandas/issues/24206) 

4371 # Push this into maybe_upcast_putmask? 

4372 # We can't pass EAs there right now. Looks a bit 

4373 # complicated. 

4374 # So we unbox the ndarray_values, op, re-box. 

4375 values_type = type(values) 

4376 values_dtype = values.dtype 

4377 

4378 if issubclass(values_type, DatetimeLikeArray): 

4379 values = values._data 

4380 

4381 if mask.any(): 

4382 values, changed = maybe_upcast_putmask( 

4383 values, mask, np.nan) 

4384 

4385 if issubclass(values_type, DatetimeLikeArray): 

4386 values = values_type(values, dtype=values_dtype) 

4387 

4388 return values 

4389 

4390 new_index = ibase.default_index(len(new_obj)) 

4391 if level is not None: 

4392 if not isinstance(level, (tuple, list)): 

4393 level = [level] 

4394 level = [self.index._get_level_number(lev) for lev in level] 

4395 if len(level) < self.index.nlevels: 

4396 new_index = self.index.droplevel(level) 

4397 

4398 if not drop: 

4399 if isinstance(self.index, MultiIndex): 

4400 names = [n if n is not None else ('level_%d' % i) 

4401 for (i, n) in enumerate(self.index.names)] 

4402 to_insert = lzip(self.index.levels, self.index.codes) 

4403 else: 

4404 default = 'index' if 'index' not in self else 'level_0' 

4405 names = ([default] if self.index.name is None 

4406 else [self.index.name]) 

4407 to_insert = ((self.index, None),) 

4408 

4409 multi_col = isinstance(self.columns, MultiIndex) 

4410 for i, (lev, lab) in reversed(list(enumerate(to_insert))): 

4411 if not (level is None or i in level): 

4412 continue 

4413 name = names[i] 

4414 if multi_col: 

4415 col_name = (list(name) if isinstance(name, tuple) 

4416 else [name]) 

4417 if col_fill is None: 

4418 if len(col_name) not in (1, self.columns.nlevels): 

4419 raise ValueError("col_fill=None is incompatible " 

4420 "with incomplete column name " 

4421 "{}".format(name)) 

4422 col_fill = col_name[0] 

4423 

4424 lev_num = self.columns._get_level_number(col_level) 

4425 name_lst = [col_fill] * lev_num + col_name 

4426 missing = self.columns.nlevels - len(name_lst) 

4427 name_lst += [col_fill] * missing 

4428 name = tuple(name_lst) 

4429 # to ndarray and maybe infer different dtype 

4430 level_values = _maybe_casted_values(lev, lab) 

4431 new_obj.insert(0, name, level_values) 

4432 

4433 new_obj.index = new_index 

4434 if not inplace: 

4435 return new_obj

4456 def dropna(self, axis=0, how='any', thresh=None, subset=None, 

4457 inplace=False): 

4458 """ 

4459 Remove missing values. 

4460 

4461 See the :ref:`User Guide <missing_data>` for more on which values are 

4462 considered missing, and how to work with missing data. 

4463 

4464 Parameters 

4465 ---------- 

4466 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0 

4467 Determine if rows or columns which contain missing values are 

4468 removed. 

4469 

4470 * 0, or 'index' : Drop rows which contain missing values. 

4471 * 1, or 'columns' : Drop columns which contain missing value. 

4472 

4473 .. deprecated:: 0.23.0

4475 Pass tuple or list to drop on multiple axes. 

4476 Only a single axis is allowed. 

4477 

4478 how : {'any', 'all'}, default 'any' 

4479 Determine if row or column is removed from DataFrame, when we have 

4480 at least one NA or all NA.

4482 * 'any' : If any NA values are present, drop that row or column. 

4483 * 'all' : If all values are NA, drop that row or column. 

4484 

4485 thresh : int, optional 

4486 Require that many non-NA values. 

4487 subset : array-like, optional 

4488 Labels along other axis to consider, e.g. if you are dropping rows 

4489 these would be a list of columns to include. 

4490 inplace : bool, default False 

4491 If True, do operation inplace and return None. 

4492 

4493 Returns 

4494 ------- 

4495 DataFrame 

4496 DataFrame with NA entries dropped from it. 

4497 

4498 See Also 

4499 -------- 

4500 DataFrame.isna: Indicate missing values. 

4501 DataFrame.notna : Indicate existing (non-missing) values. 

4502 DataFrame.fillna : Replace missing values. 

4503 Series.dropna : Drop missing values. 

4504 Index.dropna : Drop missing indices. 

4505 

4506 Examples 

4507 -------- 

4508 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"name": ['Alfred', 'Batman', 'Catwoman'], 

4509 ... "toy": [np.nan, 'Batmobile', 'Bullwhip'],

4511 ... pd.NaT]})

4523

4525

4527 name 

4528 0 Alfred 

4529 1 Batman 

4530 2 Catwoman 

4531 

4532 Drop the rows where all elements are missing. 

4533 

4534 >>> df.dropna(how='all') 

4535 name toy born 

4536 0 Alfred NaN NaT 

4537 1 Batman Batmobile 1940-04-25 

4538 2 Catwoman Bullwhip NaT 

4539 

4540 Keep only the rows with at least 2 non-NA values.

4542 >>> df.dropna(thresh=2)

4544 1 Batman Batmobile 1940-04-25 

4545 2 Catwoman Bullwhip NaT

4548

4550 name toy born 

4551 1 Batman Batmobile 1940-04-25 

4552 

4553 Keep the DataFrame with valid entries in the same variable. 

4554 

4555 >>> df.dropna(inplace=True) 

4556 >>> df 

4557 name toy born 

4558 1 Batman Batmobile 1940-04-25 

4559 """ 

4560 inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, 'inplace') 

4561 if isinstance(axis, (tuple, list)): 

4562 # GH20987 

4563 msg = ("supplying multiple axes to axis is deprecated and " 

4564 "will be removed in a future version.") 

4565 warnings.warn(msg, FutureWarning, stacklevel=2) 

4566 

4567 result = self 

4568 for ax in axis: 

4569 result = result.dropna(how=how, thresh=thresh, subset=subset, 

4570 axis=ax) 

4571 else: 

4572 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

4573 agg_axis = 1 - axis 

4574 

4575 agg_obj = self 

4576 if subset is not None: 

4577 ax = self._get_axis(agg_axis) 

4578 indices = ax.get_indexer_for(subset) 

4579 check = indices == -1 

4580 if check.any(): 

4581 raise KeyError(list(np.compress(check, subset))) 

4582 agg_obj = self.take(indices, axis=agg_axis) 

4583 

4584 count = agg_obj.count(axis=agg_axis) 

4585 

4586 if thresh is not None: 

4587 mask = count >= thresh 

4588 elif how == 'any': 

4589 mask = count == len(agg_obj._get_axis(agg_axis)) 

4590 elif how == 'all': 

4591 mask = count > 0 

4592 else: 

4593 if how is not None: 

4594 raise ValueError('invalid how option: {h}'.format(h=how)) 

4595 else: 

4596 raise TypeError('must specify how or thresh') 

4597 

4598 result = self.loc(axis=axis)[mask] 

4599 

4600 if inplace: 

4601 self._update_inplace(result) 

4602 else: 

4603 return result

4605 def drop_duplicates(self, subset=None, keep='first', inplace=False): 

4606 """ 

4607 Return DataFrame with duplicate rows removed, optionally only 

4608 considering certain columns. 

4609 

4610 Parameters 

4611 ----------

4616 - ``first`` : Drop duplicates except for the first occurrence. 

4617 - ``last`` : Drop duplicates except for the last occurrence. 

4618 - False : Drop all duplicates.

4620 Whether to drop duplicates in place or to return a copy

4626 if self.empty: 

4627 return self.copy()

4633 inds, = (-duplicated)._ndarray_values.nonzero() 

4634 new_data = self._data.take(inds) 

4635 self._update_inplace(new_data) 

4636 else:

4639 def duplicated(self, subset=None, keep='first'): 

4640 """ 

4641 Return boolean Series denoting duplicate rows, optionally only 

4642 considering certain columns. 

4643 

4644 Parameters 

4645 ---------- 

4646 subset : column label or sequence of labels, optional 

4647 Only consider certain columns for identifying duplicates, by 

4648 default use all of the columns 

4649 keep : {'first', 'last', False}, default 'first' 

4650 - ``first`` : Mark duplicates as ``True`` except for the 

4651 first occurrence. 

4652 - ``last`` : Mark duplicates as ``True`` except for the 

4653 last occurrence. 

4654 - False : Mark all duplicates as ``True``. 

4655 

4656 Returns 

4657 ------- 

4658 duplicated : Series 

4659 """ 

4660 from pandas.core.sorting import get_group_index 

4661 from pandas._libs.hashtable import duplicated_int64, _SIZE_HINT_LIMIT 

4662 

4663 if self.empty: 

4664 return Series(dtype=bool) 

4665 

4666 def f(vals): 

4667 labels, shape = algorithms.factorize( 

4668 vals, size_hint=min(len(self), _SIZE_HINT_LIMIT)) 

4669 return labels.astype('i8', copy=False), len(shape) 

4670 

4671 if subset is None: 

4672 subset = self.columns 

4673 elif (not np.iterable(subset) or 

4674 isinstance(subset, compat.string_types) or 

4675 isinstance(subset, tuple) and subset in self.columns): 

4676 subset = subset, 

4677 

4678 # Verify all columns in subset exist in the queried dataframe 

4679 # Otherwise, raise a KeyError, same as if you try to __getitem__ with a 

4680 # key that doesn't exist. 

4681 diff = Index(subset).difference(self.columns) 

4682 if not diff.empty: 

4683 raise KeyError(diff) 

4684 

4685 vals = (col.values for name, col in self.iteritems() 

4686 if name in subset) 

4687 labels, shape = map(list, zip(*map(f, vals))) 

4688 

4689 ids = get_group_index(labels, shape, sort=False, xnull=False) 

4690 return Series(duplicated_int64(ids, keep), index=self.index)

5016 """

5075 def _combine_frame(self, other, func, fill_value=None, level=None): 

5076 this, other = self.align(other, join='outer', level=level, copy=False) 

5077 new_index, new_columns = this.index, this.columns 

5078 

5079 def _arith_op(left, right): 

5080 # for the mixed_type case where we iterate over columns, 

5081 # _arith_op(left, right) is equivalent to 

5082 # left._binop(right, func, fill_value=fill_value) 

5083 left, right = ops.fill_binop(left, right, fill_value) 

5084 return func(left, right) 

5085 

5086 if ops.should_series_dispatch(this, other, func): 

5087 # iterate over columns 

5088 return ops.dispatch_to_series(this, other, _arith_op) 

5089 else: 

5090 result = _arith_op(this.values, other.values) 

5091 return self._constructor(result, 

5092 index=new_index, columns=new_columns, 

5093 copy=False) 

5094 

5095 def _combine_match_index(self, other, func, level=None): 

5096 left, right = self.align(other, join='outer', axis=0, level=level, 

5097 copy=False) 

5098 assert left.index.equals(right.index) 

5099 

5100 if left._is_mixed_type or right._is_mixed_type: 

5101 # operate column-wise; avoid costly object-casting in `.values` 

5102 return ops.dispatch_to_series(left, right, func) 

5103 else: 

5104 # fastpath --> operate directly on values 

5105 with np.errstate(all="ignore"): 

5106 new_data = func(left.values.T, right.values).T 

5107 return self._constructor(new_data, 

5108 index=left.index, columns=self.columns, 

5109 copy=False) 

5110 

5111 def _combine_match_columns(self, other, func, level=None): 

5112 assert isinstance(other, Series) 

5113 left, right = self.align(other, join='outer', axis=1, level=level, 

5114 copy=False) 

5115 assert left.columns.equals(right.index) 

5116 return ops.dispatch_to_series(left, right, func, axis="columns") 

5117 

5118 def _combine_const(self, other, func): 

5119 assert lib.is_scalar(other) or np.ndim(other) == 0 

5120 return ops.dispatch_to_series(self, other, func)

5122 def combine(self, other, func, fill_value=None, overwrite=True): 

5123 """ 

5124 Perform column-wise combine with another DataFrame based on a 

5125 passed function. 

5126 

5127 Combines a DataFrame with `other` DataFrame using `func` 

5128 to element-wise combine columns. The row and column indexes of the 

5129 resulting DataFrame will be the union of the two. 

5130 

5131 Parameters 

5132 ---------- 

5133 other : DataFrame 

5134 The DataFrame to merge column-wise. 

5135 func : function 

5136 Function that takes two series as inputs and return a Series or a 

5137 scalar. Used to merge the two dataframes column by columns. 

5138 fill_value : scalar value, default None 

5139 The value to fill NaNs with prior to passing any column to the 

5140 merge func. 

5141 overwrite : boolean, default True 

5142 If True, columns in `self` that do not exist in `other` will be 

5143 overwritten with NaNs. 

5144 

5145 Returns 

5146 ------- 

5147 result : DataFrame 

5148 

5149 See Also 

5150 -------- 

5151 DataFrame.combine_first : Combine two DataFrame objects and default to 

5152 non-null values in frame calling the method. 

5153 

5154 Examples 

5155 -------- 

5156 Combine using a simple function that chooses the smaller column. 

5157 

5158 >>> df1 = pd.DataFrame({'A': [0, 0], 'B': [4, 4]}) 

5159 >>> df2 = pd.DataFrame({'A': [1, 1], 'B': [3, 3]}) 

5160 >>> take_smaller = lambda s1, s2: s1 if s1.sum() < s2.sum() else s2 

5161 >>> df1.combine(df2, take_smaller) 

5162 A B 

5163 0 0 3 

5164 1 0 3 

5165 

5166 Example using a true element-wise combine function. 

5167 

5168 >>> df1 = pd.DataFrame({'A': [5, 0], 'B': [2, 4]}) 

5169 >>> df2 = pd.DataFrame({'A': [1, 1], 'B': [3, 3]}) 

5170 >>> df1.combine(df2, np.minimum) 

5171 A B 

5172 0 1 2 

5173 1 0 3 

5174 

5175 Using `fill_value` fills Nones prior to passing the column to the 

5176 merge function. 

5177 

5178 >>> df1 = pd.DataFrame({'A': [0, 0], 'B': [None, 4]}) 

5179 >>> df2 = pd.DataFrame({'A': [1, 1], 'B': [3, 3]}) 

5180 >>> df1.combine(df2, take_smaller, fill_value=-5) 

5181 A B 

5182 0 0 -5.0 

5183 1 0 4.0 

5184 

5185 However, if the same element in both dataframes is None, that None 

5186 is preserved 

5187 

5188 >>> df1 = pd.DataFrame({'A': [0, 0], 'B': [None, 4]}) 

5189 >>> df2 = pd.DataFrame({'A': [1, 1], 'B': [None, 3]}) 

5190 >>> df1.combine(df2, take_smaller, fill_value=-5) 

5191 A B 

5192 0 0 NaN 

5193 1 0 3.0 

5194 

5195 Example that demonstrates the use of `overwrite` and behavior when 

5196 the axis differ between the dataframes. 

5197 

5198 >>> df1 = pd.DataFrame({'A': [0, 0], 'B': [4, 4]}) 

5199 >>> df2 = pd.DataFrame({'B': [3, 3], 'C': [-10, 1],}, index=[1, 2]) 

5200 >>> df1.combine(df2, take_smaller) 

5201 A B C 

5202 0 NaN NaN NaN 

5203 1 NaN 3.0 -10.0 

5204 2 NaN 3.0 1.0 

5205 

5206 >>> df1.combine(df2, take_smaller, overwrite=False) 

5207 A B C 

5208 0 0.0 NaN NaN 

5209 1 0.0 3.0 -10.0 

5210 2 NaN 3.0 1.0 

5211 

5212 Demonstrating the preference of the passed in dataframe. 

5213 

5214 >>> df2 = pd.DataFrame({'B': [3, 3], 'C': [1, 1],}, index=[1, 2]) 

5215 >>> df2.combine(df1, take_smaller) 

5216 A B C 

5217 0 0.0 NaN NaN 

5218 1 0.0 3.0 NaN 

5219 2 NaN 3.0 NaN 

5220 

5221 >>> df2.combine(df1, take_smaller, overwrite=False) 

5222 A B C 

5223 0 0.0 NaN NaN 

5224 1 0.0 3.0 1.0 

5225 2 NaN 3.0 1.0 

5226 """ 

5227 other_idxlen = len(other.index) # save for compare 

5228 

5229 this, other = self.align(other, copy=False) 

5230 new_index = this.index 

5231 

5232 if other.empty and len(new_index) == len(self.index): 

5233 return self.copy() 

5234 

5235 if self.empty and len(other) == other_idxlen: 

5236 return other.copy() 

5237 

5238 # sorts if possible 

5239 new_columns = this.columns.union(other.columns) 

5240 do_fill = fill_value is not None 

5241 result = {} 

5242 for col in new_columns: 

5243 series = this[col] 

5244 otherSeries = other[col] 

5245 

5246 this_dtype = series.dtype 

5247 other_dtype = otherSeries.dtype 

5248 

5249 this_mask = isna(series) 

5250 other_mask = isna(otherSeries) 

5251 

5252 # don't overwrite columns unecessarily 

5253 # DO propagate if this column is not in the intersection 

5254 if not overwrite and other_mask.all(): 

5255 result[col] = this[col].copy() 

5256 continue 

5257 

5258 if do_fill: 

5259 series = series.copy() 

5260 otherSeries = otherSeries.copy() 

5261 series[this_mask] = fill_value 

5262 otherSeries[other_mask] = fill_value 

5263 

5264 if col not in self.columns: 

5265 # If self DataFrame does not have col in other DataFrame, 

5266 # try to promote series, which is all NaN, as other_dtype. 

5267 new_dtype = other_dtype 

5268 try: 

5269 series = series.astype(new_dtype, copy=False) 

5270 except ValueError: 

5271 # e.g. new_dtype is integer types 

5272 pass 

5273 else: 

5274 # if we have different dtypes, possibly promote 

5275 new_dtype = find_common_type([this_dtype, other_dtype]) 

5276 if not is_dtype_equal(this_dtype, new_dtype): 

5277 series = series.astype(new_dtype) 

5278 if not is_dtype_equal(other_dtype, new_dtype): 

5279 otherSeries = otherSeries.astype(new_dtype) 

5280 

5281 arr = func(series, otherSeries) 

5282 arr = maybe_downcast_to_dtype(arr, this_dtype) 

5283 

5284 result[col] = arr 

5285 

5286 # convert_objects just in case 

5287 return self._constructor(result, index=new_index, 

5288 columns=new_columns)

5290 def combine_first(self, other): 

5291 """ 

5292 Update null elements with value in the same location in `other`. 

5293 

5294 Combine two DataFrame objects by filling null values in one DataFrame 

5295 with non-null values from other DataFrame. The row and column indexes 

5296 of the resulting DataFrame will be the union of the two. 

5297 

5298 Parameters 

5299 ---------- 

5300 other : DataFrame 

5301 Provided DataFrame to use to fill null values. 

5302 

5303 Returns 

5304 ------- 

5305 combined : DataFrame 

5306 

5307 See Also 

5308 -------- 

5309 DataFrame.combine : Perform series-wise operation on two DataFrames 

5310 using a given function. 

5311 

5312 Examples 

5313 -------- 

5314 

5315 >>> df1 = pd.DataFrame({'A': [None, 0], 'B': [None, 4]}) 

5316 >>> df2 = pd.DataFrame({'A': [1, 1], 'B': [3, 3]})

5327 >>> df1.combine_first(df2) 

5328 A B C 

5329 0 NaN 4.0 NaN 

5330 1 0.0 3.0 1.0 

5331 2 NaN 3.0 1.0

5333 import pandas.core.computation.expressions as expressions 

5334 

5335 def extract_values(arr): 

5336 # Does two things: 

5337 # 1. maybe gets the values from the Series / Index 

5338 # 2. convert datelike to i8 

5339 if isinstance(arr, (ABCIndexClass, ABCSeries)): 

5340 arr = arr._values 

5341 

5342 if needs_i8_conversion(arr): 

5343 if is_extension_array_dtype(arr.dtype): 

5344 arr = arr.asi8 

5345 else: 

5346 arr = arr.view('i8') 

5347 return arr 

5348 

5349 def combiner(x, y): 

5350 mask = isna(x) 

5351 if isinstance(mask, (ABCIndexClass, ABCSeries)): 

5352 mask = mask._values 

5353 

5354 x_values = extract_values(x) 

5355 y_values = extract_values(y) 

5356 

5357 # If the column y in other DataFrame is not in first DataFrame, 

5358 # just return y_values. 

5359 if y.name not in self.columns: 

5360 return y_values 

5361 

5362 return expressions.where(mask, y_values, x_values) 

5363 

5364 return self.combine(other, combiner, overwrite=False)

5366 @deprecate_kwarg(old_arg_name='raise_conflict', new_arg_name='errors', 

5367 mapping={False: 'ignore', True: 'raise'}) 

5368 def update(self, other, join='left', overwrite=True, filter_func=None, 

5369 errors='ignore'): 

5370 """ 

5371 Modify in place using non-NA values from another DataFrame. 

5372 

5373 Aligns on indices. There is no return value. 

5374 

5375 Parameters 

5376 ---------- 

5377 other : DataFrame, or object coercible into a DataFrame 

5378 Should have at least one matching index/column label 

5379 with the original DataFrame. If a Series is passed, 

5380 its name attribute must be set, and that will be 

5381 used as the column name to align with the original DataFrame. 

5382 join : {'left'}, default 'left' 

5383 Only left join is implemented, keeping the index and columns of the 

5384 original object. 

5385 overwrite : bool, default True 

5386 How to handle non-NA values for overlapping keys: 

5387 

5388 * True: overwrite original DataFrame's values 

5389 with values from `other`. 

5390 * False: only update values that are NA in 

5391 the original DataFrame. 

5392 

5393 filter_func : callable(1d-array) -> bool 1d-array, optional 

5394 Can choose to replace values other than NA. Return True for values 

5395 that should be updated. 

5396 errors : {'raise', 'ignore'}, default 'ignore' 

5397 If 'raise', will raise a ValueError if the DataFrame and `other` 

5398 both contain non-NA data in the same place. 

5399 

5400 .. versionchanged :: 0.24.0 

5401 Changed from `raise_conflict=False|True` 

5402 to `errors='ignore'|'raise'`. 

5403 

5404 Returns 

5405 ------- 

5406 None : method directly changes calling object 

5407 

5408 Raises 

5409 ------ 

5410 ValueError 

5411 * When `errors='raise'` and there's overlapping non-NA data. 

5412 * When `errors` is not either `'ignore'` or `'raise'` 

5413 NotImplementedError 

5414 * If `join != 'left'` 

5415 

5416 See Also 

5417 -------- 

5418 dict.update : Similar method for dictionaries. 

5419 DataFrame.merge : For column(s)-on-columns(s) operations. 

5420 

5421 Examples 

5422 -------- 

5423 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A': [1, 2, 3], 

5424 ... 'B': [400, 500, 600]}) 

5425 >>> new_df = pd.DataFrame({'B': [4, 5, 6], 

5426 ... 'C': [7, 8, 9]}) 

5427 >>> df.update(new_df) 

5428 >>> df 

5429 A B 

5430 0 1 4 

5431 1 2 5 

5432 2 3 6 

5433 

5434 The DataFrame's length does not increase as a result of the update, 

5435 only values at matching index/column labels are updated. 

5436 

5437 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A': ['a', 'b', 'c'], 

5438 ... 'B': ['x', 'y', 'z']}) 

5439 >>> new_df = pd.DataFrame({'B': ['d', 'e', 'f', 'g', 'h', 'i']}) 

5440 >>> df.update(new_df) 

5441 >>> df 

5442 A B 

5443 0 a d 

5444 1 b e 

5445 2 c f 

5446 

5447 For Series, it's name attribute must be set. 

5448 

5449 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A': ['a', 'b', 'c'], 

5450 ... 'B': ['x', 'y', 'z']}) 

5451 >>> new_column = pd.Series(['d', 'e'], name='B', index=[0, 2]) 

5452 >>> df.update(new_column) 

5453 >>> df 

5454 A B 

5455 0 a d 

5456 1 b y 

5457 2 c e 

5458 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A': ['a', 'b', 'c'], 

5459 ... 'B': ['x', 'y', 'z']}) 

5460 >>> new_df = pd.DataFrame({'B': ['d', 'e']}, index=[1, 2]) 

5461 >>> df.update(new_df) 

5462 >>> df 

5463 A B 

5464 0 a x 

5465 1 b d 

5466 2 c e 

5467 

5468 If `other` contains NaNs the corresponding values are not updated 

5469 in the original dataframe. 

5470 

5471 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A': [1, 2, 3], 

5472 ... 'B': [400, 500, 600]}) 

5473 >>> new_df = pd.DataFrame({'B': [4, np.nan, 6]}) 

5474 >>> df.update(new_df) 

5475 >>> df 

5476 A B 

5477 0 1 4.0 

5478 1 2 500.0 

5479 2 3 6.0 

5480 """ 

5481 import pandas.core.computation.expressions as expressions 

5482 # TODO: Support other joins 

5483 if join != 'left': # pragma: no cover 

5484 raise NotImplementedError("Only left join is supported") 

5485 if errors not in ['ignore', 'raise']: 

5486 raise ValueError("The parameter errors must be either " 

5487 "'ignore' or 'raise'") 

5488 

5489 if not isinstance(other, DataFrame): 

5490 other = DataFrame(other) 

5491 

5492 other = other.reindex_like(self) 

5493 

5494 for col in self.columns: 

5495 this = self[col].values 

5496 that = other[col].values 

5497 if filter_func is not None: 

5498 with np.errstate(all='ignore'): 

5499 mask = ~filter_func(this) | isna(that) 

5500 else: 

5501 if errors == 'raise': 

5502 mask_this = notna(that) 

5503 mask_that = notna(this) 

5504 if any(mask_this & mask_that): 

5505 raise ValueError("Data overlaps.") 

5506 

5507 if overwrite: 

5508 mask = isna(that) 

5509 else: 

5510 mask = notna(this) 

5511 

5512 # don't overwrite columns unecessarily 

5513 if mask.all(): 

5514 continue 

5515 

5516 self[col] = expressions.where(mask, this, that)

5761 def stack(self, level=-1, dropna=True): 

5762 """ 

5763 Stack the prescribed level(s) from columns to index. 

5764 

5765 Return a reshaped DataFrame or Series having a multi-level 

5766 index with one or more new inner-most levels compared to the current 

5767 DataFrame. The new inner-most levels are created by pivoting the 

5768 columns of the current dataframe: 

5769 

5770 - if the columns have a single level, the output is a Series; 

5771 - if the columns have multiple levels, the new index 

5772 level(s) is (are) taken from the prescribed level(s) and 

5773 the output is a DataFrame. 

5774 

5775 The new index levels are sorted. 

5776 

5777 Parameters 

5778 ---------- 

5779 level : int, str, list, default -1 

5780 Level(s) to stack from the column axis onto the index 

5781 axis, defined as one index or label, or a list of indices 

5782 or labels. 

5783 dropna : bool, default True 

5784 Whether to drop rows in the resulting Frame/Series with 

5785 missing values. Stacking a column level onto the index 

5786 axis can create combinations of index and column values 

5787 that are missing from the original dataframe. See Examples 

5788 section. 

5789 

5790 Returns 

5791 ------- 

5792 DataFrame or Series 

5793 Stacked dataframe or series. 

5794 

5795 See Also 

5796 -------- 

5797 DataFrame.unstack : Unstack prescribed level(s) from index axis 

5798 onto column axis. 

5799 DataFrame.pivot : Reshape dataframe from long format to wide 

5800 format. 

5801 DataFrame.pivot_table : Create a spreadsheet-style pivot table 

5802 as a DataFrame. 

5803 

5804 Notes 

5805 ----- 

5806 The function is named by analogy with a collection of books 

5807 being re-organised from being side by side on a horizontal 

5808 position (the columns of the dataframe) to being stacked 

5809 vertically on top of of each other (in the index of the 

5810 dataframe). 

5811 

5812 Examples 

5813 -------- 

5814 **Single level columns** 

5815 

5816 >>> df_single_level_cols = pd.DataFrame([[0, 1], [2, 3]], 

5817 ... index=['cat', 'dog'], 

5818 ... columns=['weight', 'height']) 

5819 

5820 Stacking a dataframe with a single level column axis returns a Series: 

5821 

5822 >>> df_single_level_cols 

5823 weight height 

5824 cat 0 1 

5825 dog 2 3 

5826 >>> df_single_level_cols.stack() 

5827 cat weight 0 

5828 height 1 

5829 dog weight 2 

5830 height 3 

5831 dtype: int64 

5832 

5833 **Multi level columns: simple case** 

5834 

5835 >>> multicol1 = pd.MultiIndex.from_tuples([('weight', 'kg'), 

5836 ... ('weight', 'pounds')]) 

5837 >>> df_multi_level_cols1 = pd.DataFrame([[1, 2], [2, 4]], 

5838 ... index=['cat', 'dog'], 

5839 ... columns=multicol1) 

5840 

5841 Stacking a dataframe with a multi-level column axis: 

5842 

5843 >>> df_multi_level_cols1 

5844 weight 

5845 kg pounds 

5846 cat 1 2 

5847 dog 2 4 

5848 >>> df_multi_level_cols1.stack() 

5849 weight 

5850 cat kg 1 

5851 pounds 2 

5852 dog kg 2 

5853 pounds 4 

5854 

5855 **Missing values** 

5856 

5857 >>> multicol2 = pd.MultiIndex.from_tuples([('weight', 'kg'), 

5858 ... ('height', 'm')]) 

5859 >>> df_multi_level_cols2 = pd.DataFrame([[1.0, 2.0], [3.0, 4.0]], 

5860 ... index=['cat', 'dog'], 

5861 ... columns=multicol2) 

5862 

5863 It is common to have missing values when stacking a dataframe 

5864 with multi-level columns, as the stacked dataframe typically 

5865 has more values than the original dataframe. Missing values 

5866 are filled with NaNs: 

5867 

5868 >>> df_multi_level_cols2 

5869 weight height 

5870 kg m 

5871 cat 1.0 2.0 

5872 dog 3.0 4.0 

5873 >>> df_multi_level_cols2.stack() 

5874 height weight 

5875 cat kg NaN 1.0 

5876 m 2.0 NaN 

5877 dog kg NaN 3.0 

5878 m 4.0 NaN 

5879 

5880 **Prescribing the level(s) to be stacked** 

5881 

5882 The first parameter controls which level or levels are stacked: 

5883 

5884 >>> df_multi_level_cols2.stack(0) 

5885 kg m 

5886 cat height NaN 2.0 

5887 weight 1.0 NaN 

5888 dog height NaN 4.0 

5889 weight 3.0 NaN 

5890 >>> df_multi_level_cols2.stack([0, 1]) 

5891 cat height m 2.0 

5892 weight kg 1.0 

5893 dog height m 4.0 

5894 weight kg 3.0 

5895 dtype: float64 

5896 

5897 **Dropping missing values** 

5898 

5899 >>> df_multi_level_cols3 = pd.DataFrame([[None, 1.0], [2.0, 3.0]], 

5900 ... index=['cat', 'dog'], 

5901 ... columns=multicol2) 

5902 

5903 Note that rows where all values are missing are dropped by 

5904 default but this behaviour can be controlled via the dropna 

5905 keyword parameter: 

5906 

5907 >>> df_multi_level_cols3 

5908 weight height 

5909 kg m 

5910 cat NaN 1.0 

5911 dog 2.0 3.0 

5912 >>> df_multi_level_cols3.stack(dropna=False) 

5913 height weight 

5914 cat kg NaN NaN 

5915 m 1.0 NaN 

5916 dog kg NaN 2.0 

5917 m 3.0 NaN 

5918 >>> df_multi_level_cols3.stack(dropna=True) 

5919 height weight 

5920 cat m 1.0 NaN 

5921 dog kg NaN 2.0 

5922 m 3.0 NaN 

5923 """ 

5924 from pandas.core.reshape.reshape import stack, stack_multiple 

5925 

5926 if isinstance(level, (tuple, list)): 

5927 return stack_multiple(self, level, dropna=dropna) 

5928 else: 

5929 return stack(self, level, dropna=dropna)

5931 def unstack(self, level=-1, fill_value=None): 

5932 """ 

5933 Pivot a level of the (necessarily hierarchical) index labels, returning 

5934 a DataFrame having a new level of column labels whose inner-most level 

5935 consists of the pivoted index labels. 

5936 

5937 If the index is not a MultiIndex, the output will be a Series 

5938 (the analogue of stack when the columns are not a MultiIndex). 

5939 

5940 The level involved will automatically get sorted. 

5941 

5942 Parameters 

5943 ---------- 

5944 level : int, string, or list of these, default -1 (last level) 

5945 Level(s) of index to unstack, can pass level name 

5946 fill_value : replace NaN with this value if the unstack produces 

5947 missing values 

5948 

5949 .. versionadded:: 0.18.0 

5950 

5951 Returns 

5952 ------- 

5953 unstacked : DataFrame or Series 

5954 

5955 See Also 

5956 -------- 

5957 DataFrame.pivot : Pivot a table based on column values. 

5958 DataFrame.stack : Pivot a level of the column labels (inverse operation 

5959 from `unstack`). 

5960 

5961 Examples 

5962 -------- 

5963 >>> index = pd.MultiIndex.from_tuples([('one', 'a'), ('one', 'b'), 

5964 ... ('two', 'a'), ('two', 'b')])

5966 >>> s 

5967 one a 1.0 

5968 b 2.0 

5969 two a 3.0 

5970 b 4.0 

5971 dtype: float64 

5972

5974 a b 

5975 one 1.0 2.0 

5976 two 3.0 4.0 

5977 

5978 >>> s.unstack(level=0) 

5979 one two 

5980 a 1.0 3.0 

5981 b 2.0 4.0 

5982 

5983 >>> df = s.unstack(level=0) 

5984 >>> df.unstack() 

5985 one a 1.0 

5986 b 2.0 

5987 two a 3.0 

5988 b 4.0 

5989 dtype: float64 

5990 """ 

5991 from pandas.core.reshape.reshape import unstack 

5992 return unstack(self, level, fill_value)

6310 def apply(self, func, axis=0, broadcast=None, raw=False, reduce=None, 

6311 result_type=None, args=(), **kwds): 

6312 """ 

6313 Apply a function along an axis of the DataFrame. 

6314 

6315 Objects passed to the function are Series objects whose index is 

6316 either the DataFrame's index (``axis=0``) or the DataFrame's columns 

6317 (``axis=1``). By default (``result_type=None``), the final return type 

6318 is inferred from the return type of the applied function. Otherwise, 

6319 it depends on the `result_type` argument. 

6320 

6321 Parameters 

6322 ---------- 

6323 func : function 

6324 Function to apply to each column or row. 

6325 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0 

6326 Axis along which the function is applied: 

6327 

6328 * 0 or 'index': apply function to each column. 

6329 * 1 or 'columns': apply function to each row. 

6330 broadcast : bool, optional 

6331 Only relevant for aggregation functions: 

6332 

6333 * ``False`` or ``None`` : returns a Series whose length is the 

6334 length of the index or the number of columns (based on the 

6335 `axis` parameter) 

6336 * ``True`` : results will be broadcast to the original shape 

6337 of the frame, the original index and columns will be retained. 

6338 

6339 .. deprecated:: 0.23.0 

6340 This argument will be removed in a future version, replaced 

6341 by result_type='broadcast'. 

6342 

6343 raw : bool, default False 

6344 * ``False`` : passes each row or column as a Series to the 

6345 function. 

6346 * ``True`` : the passed function will receive ndarray objects 

6347 instead. 

6348 If you are just applying a NumPy reduction function this will 

6349 achieve much better performance. 

6350 reduce : bool or None, default None 

6351 Try to apply reduction procedures. If the DataFrame is empty, 

6352 `apply` will use `reduce` to determine whether the result 

6353 should be a Series or a DataFrame. If ``reduce=None`` (the 

6354 default), `apply`'s return value will be guessed by calling 

6355 `func` on an empty Series 

6356 (note: while guessing, exceptions raised by `func` will be 

6357 ignored). 

6358 If ``reduce=True`` a Series will always be returned, and if 

6359 ``reduce=False`` a DataFrame will always be returned. 

6360 

6361 .. deprecated:: 0.23.0 

6362 This argument will be removed in a future version, replaced 

6363 by ``result_type='reduce'``. 

6364 

6365 result_type : {'expand', 'reduce', 'broadcast', None}, default None 

6366 These only act when ``axis=1`` (columns): 

6367 

6368 * 'expand' : list-like results will be turned into columns. 

6369 * 'reduce' : returns a Series if possible rather than expanding 

6370 list-like results. This is the opposite of 'expand'. 

6371 * 'broadcast' : results will be broadcast to the original shape 

6372 of the DataFrame, the original index and columns will be 

6373 retained. 

6374 

6375 The default behaviour (None) depends on the return value of the 

6376 applied function: list-like results will be returned as a Series 

6377 of those. However if the apply function returns a Series these 

6378 are expanded to columns. 

6379 

6380 .. versionadded:: 0.23.0 

6381 

6382 args : tuple 

6383 Positional arguments to pass to `func` in addition to the 

6384 array/series. 

6385 **kwds 

6386 Additional keyword arguments to pass as keywords arguments to 

6387 `func`. 

6388 

6389 Returns 

6390 ------- 

6391 applied : Series or DataFrame 

6392 

6393 See Also 

6394 -------- 

6395 DataFrame.applymap: For elementwise operations. 

6396 DataFrame.aggregate: Only perform aggregating type operations. 

6397 DataFrame.transform: Only perform transforming type operations. 

6398 

6399 Notes 

6400 ----- 

6401 In the current implementation apply calls `func` twice on the 

6402 first column/row to decide whether it can take a fast or slow 

6403 code path. This can lead to unexpected behavior if `func` has 

6404 side-effects, as they will take effect twice for the first 

6405 column/row. 

6406 

6407 Examples 

6408 -------- 

6409 

6410 >>> df = pd.DataFrame([[4, 9],] * 3, columns=['A', 'B']) 

6411 >>> df 

6412 A B 

6413 0 4 9 

6414 1 4 9 

6415 2 4 9 

6416 

6417 Using a numpy universal function (in this case the same as 

6418 ``np.sqrt(df)``): 

6419 

6420 >>> df.apply(np.sqrt) 

6421 A B 

6422 0 2.0 3.0 

6423 1 2.0 3.0 

6424 2 2.0 3.0 

6425 

6426 Using a reducing function on either axis 

6427 

6428 >>> df.apply(np.sum, axis=0) 

6429 A 12 

6430 B 27 

6431 dtype: int64 

6432 

6433 >>> df.apply(np.sum, axis=1) 

6434 0 13 

6435 1 13 

6436 2 13 

6437 dtype: int64 

6438 

6439 Retuning a list-like will result in a Series 

6440 

6441 >>> df.apply(lambda x: [1, 2], axis=1) 

6442 0 [1, 2] 

6443 1 [1, 2] 

6444 2 [1, 2] 

6445 dtype: object 

6446 

6447 Passing result_type='expand' will expand list-like results 

6448 to columns of a Dataframe 

6449 

6450 >>> df.apply(lambda x: [1, 2], axis=1, result_type='expand') 

6451 0 1 

6452 0 1 2 

6453 1 1 2 

6454 2 1 2 

6455 

6456 Returning a Series inside the function is similar to passing 

6457 ``result_type='expand'``. The resulting column names 

6458 will be the Series index. 

6459 

6460 >>> df.apply(lambda x: pd.Series([1, 2], index=['foo', 'bar']), axis=1) 

6461 foo bar 

6462 0 1 2 

6463 1 1 2 

6464 2 1 2 

6465 

6466 Passing ``result_type='broadcast'`` will ensure the same shape 

6467 result, whether list-like or scalar is returned by the function, 

6468 and broadcast it along the axis. The resulting column names will 

6469 be the originals. 

6470 

6471 >>> df.apply(lambda x: [1, 2], axis=1, result_type='broadcast') 

6472 A B 

6473 0 1 2 

6474 1 1 2 

6475 2 1 2 

6476 """ 

6477 from pandas.core.apply import frame_apply 

6478 op = frame_apply(self, 

6479 func=func, 

6480 axis=axis, 

6481 broadcast=broadcast, 

6482 raw=raw, 

6483 reduce=reduce, 

6484 result_type=result_type, 

6485 args=args, 

6486 kwds=kwds) 

6487 return op.get_result()

6496 Parameters

6506 See Also 

6507 -------- 

6508 DataFrame.apply : Apply a function along input axis of DataFrame. 

6509 

6510 Notes 

6511 ----- 

6512 In the current implementation applymap calls `func` twice on the 

6513 first column/row to decide whether it can take a fast or slow 

6514 code path. This can lead to unexpected behavior if `func` has 

6515 side-effects, as they will take effect twice for the first 

6516 column/row. 

6517 

6518 Examples 

6519 -------- 

6520 >>> df = pd.DataFrame([[1, 2.12], [3.356, 4.567]]) 

6521 >>> df 

6522 0 1 

6523 0 1.000 2.120 

6524 1 3.356 4.567 

6525 

6526 >>> df.applymap(lambda x: len(str(x))) 

6527 0 1 

6528 0 3 4 

6529 1 5 5 

6530 

6531 Note that a vectorized version of `func` often exists, which will 

6532 be much faster. You could square each number elementwise. 

6533 

6534 >>> df.applymap(lambda x: x**2) 

6535 0 1 

6536 0 1.000000 4.494400 

6537 1 11.262736 20.857489 

6538 

6539 But it's better to avoid applymap in that case. 

6540 

6541 >>> df ** 2 

6542 0 1 

6543 0 1.000000 4.494400 

6544 1 11.262736 20.857489 

6545 """ 

6546

6548 def infer(x): 

6549 if x.empty: 

6550 return lib.map_infer(x, func) 

6551 return lib.map_infer(x.astype(object).values, func) 

6552 

6553 return self.apply(infer)

6558 def append(self, other, ignore_index=False,

6640 3 3

6649 1 1

6651 3 3 

6652 4 4

6654 if isinstance(other, (Series, dict)): 

6655 if isinstance(other, dict): 

6656 other = Series(other) 

6657 if other.name is None and not ignore_index: 

6658 raise TypeError('Can only append a Series if ignore_index=True' 

6659 ' or if the Series has a name') 

6660 

6661 if other.name is None: 

6662 index = None 

6663 else: 

6664 # other must have the same index name as self, otherwise 

6665 # index name will be reset 

6666 index = Index([other.name], name=self.index.name) 

6667 

6668 idx_diff = other.index.difference(self.columns) 

6669 try: 

6670 combined_columns = self.columns.append(idx_diff) 

6671 except TypeError:

6673 other = other.reindex(combined_columns, copy=False)

6675 index=index,

6678 if not self.columns.equals(combined_columns):

6680 elif isinstance(other, list) and not isinstance(other[0], DataFrame): 

6681 other = DataFrame(other) 

6682 if (self.columns.get_indexer(other.columns) >= 0).all(): 

6683 other = other.loc[:, self.columns] 

6684 

6685 from pandas.core.reshape.concat import concat

6687 to_concat = [self] + other 

6688 else:

6694 def join(self, other, on=None, how='left', lsuffix='', rsuffix='', 

6695 sort=False): 

6696 """ 

6697 Join columns of another DataFrame. 

6698 

6699 Join columns with `other` DataFrame either on index or on a key 

6700 column. Efficiently join multiple DataFrame objects by index at once by 

6701 passing a list. 

6702 

6703 Parameters 

6704 ---------- 

6705 other : DataFrame, Series, or list of DataFrame 

6706 Index should be similar to one of the columns in this one. If a 

6707 Series is passed, its name attribute must be set, and that will be 

6708 used as the column name in the resulting joined DataFrame. 

6709 on : str, list of str, or array-like, optional 

6710 Column or index level name(s) in the caller to join on the index 

6711 in `other`, otherwise joins index-on-index. If multiple 

6712 values given, the `other` DataFrame must have a MultiIndex. Can 

6713 pass an array as the join key if it is not already contained in 

6714 the calling DataFrame. Like an Excel VLOOKUP operation. 

6715 how : {'left', 'right', 'outer', 'inner'}, default 'left' 

6716 How to handle the operation of the two objects. 

6717 

6718 * left: use calling frame's index (or column if on is specified) 

6719 * right: use `other`'s index. 

6720 * outer: form union of calling frame's index (or column if on is 

6721 specified) with `other`'s index, and sort it. 

6722 lexicographically. 

6723 * inner: form intersection of calling frame's index (or column if 

6724 on is specified) with `other`'s index, preserving the order 

6725 of the calling's one. 

6726 lsuffix : str, default '' 

6727 Suffix to use from left frame's overlapping columns. 

6728 rsuffix : str, default '' 

6729 Suffix to use from right frame's overlapping columns. 

6730 sort : bool, default False 

6731 Order result DataFrame lexicographically by the join key. If False, 

6732 the order of the join key depends on the join type (how keyword). 

6733 

6734 Returns 

6735 ------- 

6736 DataFrame 

6737 A dataframe containing columns from both the caller and `other`. 

6738 

6739 See Also 

6740 -------- 

6741 DataFrame.merge : For column(s)-on-columns(s) operations. 

6742 

6743 Notes 

6744 ----- 

6745 Parameters `on`, `lsuffix`, and `rsuffix` are not supported when 

6746 passing a list of `DataFrame` objects. 

6747 

6748 Support for specifying index levels as the `on` parameter was added 

6749 in version 0.23.0. 

6750 

6751 Examples 

6752 -------- 

6753 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'key': ['K0', 'K1', 'K2', 'K3', 'K4', 'K5'], 

6754 ... 'A': ['A0', 'A1', 'A2', 'A3', 'A4', 'A5']}) 

6755 

6756 >>> df 

6757 key A 

6758 0 K0 A0 

6759 1 K1 A1 

6760 2 K2 A2 

6761 3 K3 A3 

6762 4 K4 A4 

6763 5 K5 A5 

6764 

6765 >>> other = pd.DataFrame({'key': ['K0', 'K1', 'K2'], 

6766 ... 'B': ['B0', 'B1', 'B2']}) 

6767 

6768 >>> other 

6769 key B 

6770 0 K0 B0 

6771 1 K1 B1 

6772 2 K2 B2 

6773 

6774 Join DataFrames using their indexes. 

6775 

6776 >>> df.join(other, lsuffix='_caller', rsuffix='_other') 

6777 key_caller A key_other B 

6778 0 K0 A0 K0 B0 

6779 1 K1 A1 K1 B1 

6780 2 K2 A2 K2 B2 

6781 3 K3 A3 NaN NaN 

6782 4 K4 A4 NaN NaN 

6783 5 K5 A5 NaN NaN 

6784 

6785 If we want to join using the key columns, we need to set key to be 

6786 the index in both `df` and `other`. The joined DataFrame will have 

6787 key as its index. 

6788 

6789 >>> df.set_index('key').join(other.set_index('key')) 

6790 A B 

6791 key 

6792 K0 A0 B0 

6793 K1 A1 B1 

6794 K2 A2 B2 

6795 K3 A3 NaN 

6796 K4 A4 NaN 

6797 K5 A5 NaN 

6798 

6799 Another option to join using the key columns is to use the `on` 

6800 parameter. DataFrame.join always uses `other`'s index but we can use 

6801 any column in `df`. This method preserves the original DataFrame's 

6802 index in the result. 

6803 

6804 >>> df.join(other.set_index('key'), on='key') 

6805 key A B 

6806 0 K0 A0 B0 

6807 1 K1 A1 B1 

6808 2 K2 A2 B2 

6809 3 K3 A3 NaN 

6810 4 K4 A4 NaN 

6811 5 K5 A5 NaN 

6812 """ 

6813 # For SparseDataFrame's benefit 

6814 return self._join_compat(other, on=on, how=how, lsuffix=lsuffix, 

6815 rsuffix=rsuffix, sort=sort)

6960 def corr(self, method='pearson', min_periods=1): 

6961 """ 

6962 Compute pairwise correlation of columns, excluding NA/null values. 

6963 

6964 Parameters 

6965 ---------- 

6966 method : {'pearson', 'kendall', 'spearman'} or callable 

6967 * pearson : standard correlation coefficient 

6968 * kendall : Kendall Tau correlation coefficient 

6969 * spearman : Spearman rank correlation 

6970 * callable: callable with input two 1d ndarrays 

6971 and returning a float 

6972 .. versionadded:: 0.24.0 

6973 

6974 min_periods : int, optional 

6975 Minimum number of observations required per pair of columns 

6976 to have a valid result. Currently only available for pearson 

6977 and spearman correlation 

6978 

6979 Returns 

6980 ------- 

6981 y : DataFrame 

6982 

6983 See Also 

6984 -------- 

6985 DataFrame.corrwith 

6986 Series.corr 

6987 

6988 Examples 

6989 -------- 

6990 >>> histogram_intersection = lambda a, b: np.minimum(a, b 

6991 ... ).sum().round(decimals=1) 

6992 >>> df = pd.DataFrame([(.2, .3), (.0, .6), (.6, .0), (.2, .1)], 

6993 ... columns=['dogs', 'cats']) 

6994 >>> df.corr(method=histogram_intersection) 

6995 dogs cats 

6996 dogs 1.0 0.3 

6997 cats 0.3 1.0 

6998 """ 

6999 numeric_df = self._get_numeric_data() 

7000 cols = numeric_df.columns 

7001 idx = cols.copy() 

7002 mat = numeric_df.values 

7003 

7004 if method == 'pearson': 

7005 correl = libalgos.nancorr(ensure_float64(mat), minp=min_periods) 

7006 elif method == 'spearman': 

7007 correl = libalgos.nancorr_spearman(ensure_float64(mat), 

7008 minp=min_periods) 

7009 elif method == 'kendall' or callable(method): 

7010 if min_periods is None: 

7011 min_periods = 1 

7012 mat = ensure_float64(mat).T 

7013 corrf = nanops.get_corr_func(method) 

7014 K = len(cols) 

7015 correl = np.empty((K, K), dtype=float) 

7016 mask = np.isfinite(mat) 

7017 for i, ac in enumerate(mat): 

7018 for j, bc in enumerate(mat): 

7019 if i > j: 

7020 continue 

7021 

7022 valid = mask[i] & mask[j] 

7023 if valid.sum() < min_periods: 

7024 c = np.nan 

7025 elif i == j: 

7026 c = 1. 

7027 elif not valid.all(): 

7028 c = corrf(ac[valid], bc[valid]) 

7029 else: 

7030 c = corrf(ac, bc) 

7031 correl[i, j] = c 

7032 correl[j, i] = c 

7033 else: 

7034 raise ValueError("method must be either 'pearson', " 

7035 "'spearman', or 'kendall', '{method}' " 

7036 "was supplied".format(method=method)) 

7037 

7038 return self._constructor(correl, index=idx, columns=cols) 

7039 

7040 def cov(self, min_periods=None): 

7041 """ 

7042 Compute pairwise covariance of columns, excluding NA/null values. 

7043 

7044 Compute the pairwise covariance among the series of a DataFrame. 

7045 The returned data frame is the `covariance matrix 

7046 <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Covariance_matrix>`__ of the columns 

7047 of the DataFrame. 

7048 

7049 Both NA and null values are automatically excluded from the 

7050 calculation. (See the note below about bias from missing values.) 

7051 A threshold can be set for the minimum number of 

7052 observations for each value created. Comparisons with observations 

7053 below this threshold will be returned as ``NaN``. 

7054 

7055 This method is generally used for the analysis of time series data to 

7056 understand the relationship between different measures 

7057 across time. 

7058 

7059 Parameters 

7060 ---------- 

7061 min_periods : int, optional 

7062 Minimum number of observations required per pair of columns 

7063 to have a valid result. 

7064 

7065 Returns 

7066 ------- 

7067 DataFrame 

7068 The covariance matrix of the series of the DataFrame. 

7069 

7070 See Also 

7071 -------- 

7072 pandas.Series.cov : Compute covariance with another Series. 

7073 pandas.core.window.EWM.cov: Exponential weighted sample covariance. 

7074 pandas.core.window.Expanding.cov : Expanding sample covariance. 

7075 pandas.core.window.Rolling.cov : Rolling sample covariance. 

7076 

7077 Notes 

7078 ----- 

7079 Returns the covariance matrix of the DataFrame's time series. 

7080 The covariance is normalized by N-1. 

7081 

7082 For DataFrames that have Series that are missing data (assuming that 

7083 data is `missing at random 

7084 <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Missing_data#Missing_at_random>`__) 

7085 the returned covariance matrix will be an unbiased estimate 

7086 of the variance and covariance between the member Series. 

7087 

7088 However, for many applications this estimate may not be acceptable 

7089 because the estimate covariance matrix is not guaranteed to be positive 

7090 semi-definite. This could lead to estimate correlations having 

7091 absolute values which are greater than one, and/or a non-invertible 

7092 covariance matrix. See `Estimation of covariance matrices 

7093 <http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Estimation_of_covariance_ 

7094 matrices>`__ for more details. 

7095 

7096 Examples 

7097 -------- 

7098 >>> df = pd.DataFrame([(1, 2), (0, 3), (2, 0), (1, 1)], 

7099 ... columns=['dogs', 'cats']) 

7100 >>> df.cov() 

7101 dogs cats 

7102 dogs 0.666667 -1.000000 

7103 cats -1.000000 1.666667 

7104 

7105 >>> np.random.seed(42) 

7106 >>> df = pd.DataFrame(np.random.randn(1000, 5), 

7107 ... columns=['a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e']) 

7108 >>> df.cov() 

7109 a b c d e 

7110 a 0.998438 -0.020161 0.059277 -0.008943 0.014144 

7111 b -0.020161 1.059352 -0.008543 -0.024738 0.009826 

7112 c 0.059277 -0.008543 1.010670 -0.001486 -0.000271 

7113 d -0.008943 -0.024738 -0.001486 0.921297 -0.013692 

7114 e 0.014144 0.009826 -0.000271 -0.013692 0.977795 

7115 

7116 **Minimum number of periods** 

7117 

7118 This method also supports an optional ``min_periods`` keyword 

7119 that specifies the required minimum number of non-NA observations for 

7120 each column pair in order to have a valid result: 

7121 

7122 >>> np.random.seed(42) 

7123 >>> df = pd.DataFrame(np.random.randn(20, 3), 

7124 ... columns=['a', 'b', 'c']) 

7125 >>> df.loc[df.index[:5], 'a'] = np.nan 

7126 >>> df.loc[df.index[5:10], 'b'] = np.nan 

7127 >>> df.cov(min_periods=12) 

7128 a b c 

7129 a 0.316741 NaN -0.150812 

7130 b NaN 1.248003 0.191417 

7131 c -0.150812 0.191417 0.895202 

7132 """ 

7133 numeric_df = self._get_numeric_data() 

7134 cols = numeric_df.columns 

7135 idx = cols.copy() 

7136 mat = numeric_df.values 

7137 

7138 if notna(mat).all(): 

7139 if min_periods is not None and min_periods > len(mat): 

7140 baseCov = np.empty((mat.shape[1], mat.shape[1])) 

7141 baseCov.fill(np.nan) 

7142 else: 

7143 baseCov = np.cov(mat.T) 

7144 baseCov = baseCov.reshape((len(cols), len(cols))) 

7145 else: 

7146 baseCov = libalgos.nancorr(ensure_float64(mat), cov=True, 

7147 minp=min_periods) 

7148 

7149 return self._constructor(baseCov, index=idx, columns=cols)

7151 def corrwith(self, other, axis=0, drop=False, method='pearson'): 

7152 """ 

7153 Compute pairwise correlation between rows or columns of DataFrame 

7154 with rows or columns of Series or DataFrame. DataFrames are first 

7155 aligned along both axes before computing the correlations. 

7156 

7157 Parameters 

7158 ---------- 

7159 other : DataFrame, Series 

7160 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0 

7161 0 or 'index' to compute column-wise, 1 or 'columns' for row-wise 

7162 drop : boolean, default False 

7163 Drop missing indices from result 

7164 method : {'pearson', 'kendall', 'spearman'} or callable 

7165 * pearson : standard correlation coefficient 

7166 * kendall : Kendall Tau correlation coefficient 

7167 * spearman : Spearman rank correlation 

7168 * callable: callable with input two 1d ndarrays 

7169 and returning a float 

7170 

7171 .. versionadded:: 0.24.0 

7172 

7173 Returns 

7174 ------- 

7175 correls : Series 

7176 

7177 See Also 

7178 ------- 

7179 DataFrame.corr 

7180 """ 

7181 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

7182 this = self._get_numeric_data() 

7183 

7184 if isinstance(other, Series): 

7185 return this.apply(lambda x: other.corr(x, method=method), 

7186 axis=axis) 

7187 

7188 other = other._get_numeric_data() 

7189 left, right = this.align(other, join='inner', copy=False) 

7190 

7191 if axis == 1: 

7192 left = left.T 

7193 right = right.T 

7194 

7195 if method == 'pearson': 

7196 # mask missing values 

7197 left = left + right * 0 

7198 right = right + left * 0 

7199 

7200 # demeaned data 

7201 ldem = left - left.mean() 

7202 rdem = right - right.mean() 

7203 

7204 num = (ldem * rdem).sum() 

7205 dom = (left.count() - 1) * left.std() * right.std() 

7206 

7207 correl = num / dom 

7208 

7209 elif method in ['kendall', 'spearman'] or callable(method): 

7210 def c(x): 

7211 return nanops.nancorr(x[0], x[1], method=method) 

7212 

7213 correl = Series(map(c, 

7214 zip(left.values.T, right.values.T)), 

7215 index=left.columns) 

7216 

7217 else: 

7218 raise ValueError("Invalid method {method} was passed, " 

7219 "valid methods are: 'pearson', 'kendall', " 

7220 "'spearman', or callable". 

7221 format(method=method)) 

7222 

7223 if not drop: 

7224 # Find non-matching labels along the given axis 

7225 # and append missing correlations (GH 22375) 

7226 raxis = 1 if axis == 0 else 0 

7227 result_index = (this._get_axis(raxis). 

7228 union(other._get_axis(raxis))) 

7229 idx_diff = result_index.difference(correl.index) 

7230 

7231 if len(idx_diff) > 0: 

7232 correl = correl.append(Series([np.nan] * len(idx_diff), 

7233 index=idx_diff)) 

7234 

7235 return correl

7240 def count(self, axis=0, level=None, numeric_only=False): 

7241 """ 

7242 Count non-NA cells for each column or row. 

7243 

7244 The values `None`, `NaN`, `NaT`, and optionally `numpy.inf` (depending 

7245 on `pandas.options.mode.use_inf_as_na`) are considered NA. 

7246 

7247 Parameters 

7248 ---------- 

7249 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0 

7250 If 0 or 'index' counts are generated for each column. 

7251 If 1 or 'columns' counts are generated for each **row**. 

7252 level : int or str, optional 

7253 If the axis is a `MultiIndex` (hierarchical), count along a 

7254 particular `level`, collapsing into a `DataFrame`. 

7255 A `str` specifies the level name. 

7256 numeric_only : boolean, default False 

7257 Include only `float`, `int` or `boolean` data. 

7258 

7259 Returns 

7260 ------- 

7261 Series or DataFrame 

7262 For each column/row the number of non-NA/null entries. 

7263 If `level` is specified returns a `DataFrame`. 

7264 

7265 See Also 

7266 -------- 

7267 Series.count: Number of non-NA elements in a Series. 

7268 DataFrame.shape: Number of DataFrame rows and columns (including NA 

7269 elements). 

7270 DataFrame.isna: Boolean same-sized DataFrame showing places of NA 

7271 elements. 

7272 

7273 Examples 

7274 -------- 

7275 Constructing DataFrame from a dictionary: 

7276 

7277 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"Person": 

7278 ... ["John", "Myla", "Lewis", "John", "Myla"], 

7279 ... "Age": [24., np.nan, 21., 33, 26], 

7280 ... "Single": [False, True, True, True, False]}) 

7281 >>> df 

7282 Person Age Single 

7283 0 John 24.0 False 

7284 1 Myla NaN True 

7285 2 Lewis 21.0 True 

7286 3 John 33.0 True 

7287 4 Myla 26.0 False 

7288 

7289 Notice the uncounted NA values: 

7290 

7291 >>> df.count() 

7292 Person 5 

7293 Age 4 

7294 Single 5 

7295 dtype: int64 

7296 

7297 Counts for each **row**: 

7298 

7299 >>> df.count(axis='columns') 

7300 0 3 

7301 1 2 

7302 2 3 

7303 3 3 

7304 4 3 

7305 dtype: int64 

7306 

7307 Counts for one level of a `MultiIndex`: 

7308 

7309 >>> df.set_index(["Person", "Single"]).count(level="Person") 

7310 Age 

7311 Person 

7312 John 2 

7313 Lewis 1 

7314 Myla 1 

7315 """ 

7316 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

7317 if level is not None: 

7318 return self._count_level(level, axis=axis, 

7319 numeric_only=numeric_only) 

7320 

7321 if numeric_only: 

7322 frame = self._get_numeric_data() 

7323 else: 

7324 frame = self 

7325 

7326 # GH #423 

7327 if len(frame._get_axis(axis)) == 0: 

7328 result = Series(0, index=frame._get_agg_axis(axis)) 

7329 else: 

7330 if frame._is_mixed_type or frame._data.any_extension_types: 

7331 # the or any_extension_types is really only hit for single- 

7332 # column frames with an extension array 

7333 result = notna(frame).sum(axis=axis) 

7334 else: 

7335 # GH13407 

7336 series_counts = notna(frame).sum(axis=axis) 

7337 counts = series_counts.values 

7338 result = Series(counts, index=frame._get_agg_axis(axis)) 

7339 

7340 return result.astype('int64')

7342 def _count_level(self, level, axis=0, numeric_only=False): 

7343 if numeric_only: 

7344 frame = self._get_numeric_data() 

7345 else: 

7346 frame = self 

7347 

7348 count_axis = frame._get_axis(axis) 

7349 agg_axis = frame._get_agg_axis(axis) 

7350 

7351 if not isinstance(count_axis, MultiIndex): 

7352 raise TypeError("Can only count levels on hierarchical " 

7353 "{ax}.".format(ax=self._get_axis_name(axis))) 

7354 

7355 if frame._is_mixed_type: 

7356 # Since we have mixed types, calling notna(frame.values) might 

7357 # upcast everything to object 

7358 mask = notna(frame).values 

7359 else: 

7360 # But use the speedup when we have homogeneous dtypes 

7361 mask = notna(frame.values) 

7362 

7363 if axis == 1: 

7364 # We're transposing the mask rather than frame to avoid potential 

7365 # upcasts to object, which induces a ~20x slowdown 

7366 mask = mask.T 

7367 

7368 if isinstance(level, compat.string_types): 

7369 level = count_axis._get_level_number(level) 

7370 

7371 level_index = count_axis.levels[level] 

7372 level_codes = ensure_int64(count_axis.codes[level]) 

7373 counts = lib.count_level_2d(mask, level_codes, len(level_index), 

7374 axis=0) 

7375 

7376 result = DataFrame(counts, index=level_index, columns=agg_axis) 

7377 

7378 if axis == 1: 

7379 # Undo our earlier transpose 

7380 return result.T 

7381 else: 

7382 return result

7384 def _reduce(self, op, name, axis=0, skipna=True, numeric_only=None, 

7385 filter_type=None, **kwds): 

7386 if axis is None and filter_type == 'bool': 

7387 labels = None 

7388 constructor = None 

7389 else: 

7390 # TODO: Make other agg func handle axis=None properly 

7391 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

7392 labels = self._get_agg_axis(axis) 

7393 constructor = self._constructor 

7394 

7395 def f(x): 

7396 return op(x, axis=axis, skipna=skipna, **kwds) 

7397 

7398 # exclude timedelta/datetime unless we are uniform types 

7399 if (axis == 1 and self._is_datelike_mixed_type 

7400 and (not self._is_homogeneous_type 

7401 and not is_datetime64tz_dtype(self.dtypes[0]))): 

7402 numeric_only = True 

7403 

7404 if numeric_only is None: 

7405 try: 

7406 values = self.values 

7407 result = f(values) 

7408 

7409 if (filter_type == 'bool' and is_object_dtype(values) and 

7410 axis is None): 

7411 # work around https://github.com/numpy/numpy/issues/10489 

7412 # TODO: combine with hasattr(result, 'dtype') further down 

7413 # hard since we don't have `values` down there. 

7414 result = np.bool_(result) 

7415 except Exception as e: 

7416 

7417 # try by-column first 

7418 if filter_type is None and axis == 0: 

7419 try: 

7420 

7421 # this can end up with a non-reduction 

7422 # but not always. if the types are mixed 

7423 # with datelike then need to make sure a series 

7424 

7425 # we only end up here if we have not specified 

7426 # numeric_only and yet we have tried a 

7427 # column-by-column reduction, where we have mixed type. 

7428 # So let's just do what we can 

7429 from pandas.core.apply import frame_apply 

7430 opa = frame_apply(self, 

7431 func=f, 

7432 result_type='expand', 

7433 ignore_failures=True) 

7434 result = opa.get_result() 

7435 if result.ndim == self.ndim: 

7436 result = result.iloc[0] 

7437 return result 

7438 except Exception: 

7439 pass 

7440 

7441 if filter_type is None or filter_type == 'numeric': 

7442 data = self._get_numeric_data() 

7443 elif filter_type == 'bool': 

7444 data = self._get_bool_data() 

7445 else: # pragma: no cover 

7446 e = NotImplementedError( 

7447 "Handling exception with filter_type {f} not" 

7448 "implemented.".format(f=filter_type)) 

7449 raise_with_traceback(e) 

7450 with np.errstate(all='ignore'): 

7451 result = f(data.values) 

7452 labels = data._get_agg_axis(axis) 

7453 else: 

7454 if numeric_only: 

7455 if filter_type is None or filter_type == 'numeric': 

7456 data = self._get_numeric_data() 

7457 elif filter_type == 'bool': 

7458 # GH 25101, # GH 24434 

7459 data = self._get_bool_data() if axis == 0 else self 

7460 else: # pragma: no cover 

7461 msg = ("Generating numeric_only data with filter_type {f}" 

7462 "not supported.".format(f=filter_type)) 

7463 raise NotImplementedError(msg) 

7464 values = data.values 

7465 labels = data._get_agg_axis(axis) 

7466 else: 

7467 values = self.values 

7468 result = f(values) 

7469 

7470 if hasattr(result, 'dtype') and is_object_dtype(result.dtype): 

7471 try: 

7472 if filter_type is None or filter_type == 'numeric': 

7473 result = result.astype(np.float64) 

7474 elif filter_type == 'bool' and notna(result).all(): 

7475 result = result.astype(np.bool_) 

7476 except (ValueError, TypeError): 

7477 

7478 # try to coerce to the original dtypes item by item if we can 

7479 if axis == 0: 

7480 result = coerce_to_dtypes(result, self.dtypes) 

7481 

7482 if constructor is not None: 

7483 result = Series(result, index=labels) 

7484 return result

7611 def mode(self, axis=0, numeric_only=False, dropna=True): 

7612 """ 

7613 Get the mode(s) of each element along the selected axis. 

7614 

7615 The mode of a set of values is the value that appears most often. 

7616 It can be multiple values. 

7617 

7618 Parameters 

7619 ---------- 

7620 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0 

7621 The axis to iterate over while searching for the mode: 

7622 

7623 * 0 or 'index' : get mode of each column 

7624 * 1 or 'columns' : get mode of each row 

7625 numeric_only : bool, default False 

7626 If True, only apply to numeric columns.

7629

7631 

7632 Returns 

7633 ------- 

7634 DataFrame 

7635 The modes of each column or row. 

7636

7638 -------- 

7639 Series.mode : Return the highest frequency value in a Series. 

7640 Series.value_counts : Return the counts of values in a Series.

7697 def quantile(self, q=0.5, axis=0, numeric_only=True, 

7698 interpolation='linear'): 

7699 """ 

7700 Return values at the given quantile over requested axis. 

7701 

7702 Parameters 

7703 ---------- 

7704 q : float or array-like, default 0.5 (50% quantile) 

7705 Value between 0 <= q <= 1, the quantile(s) to compute. 

7706 axis : {0, 1, 'index', 'columns'} (default 0) 

7707 Equals 0 or 'index' for row-wise, 1 or 'columns' for column-wise. 

7708 numeric_only : bool, default True 

7709 If False, the quantile of datetime and timedelta data will be 

7710 computed as well. 

7711 interpolation : {'linear', 'lower', 'higher', 'midpoint', 'nearest'} 

7712 This optional parameter specifies the interpolation method to use, 

7713 when the desired quantile lies between two data points `i` and `j`: 

7714 

7715 * linear: `i + (j - i) * fraction`, where `fraction` is the 

7716 fractional part of the index surrounded by `i` and `j`. 

7717 * lower: `i`. 

7718 * higher: `j`. 

7719 * nearest: `i` or `j` whichever is nearest. 

7720 * midpoint: (`i` + `j`) / 2. 

7721 

7722 .. versionadded:: 0.18.0 

7723 

7724 Returns 

7725 ------- 

7726 quantiles : Series or DataFrame 

7727 

7728 - If ``q`` is an array, a DataFrame will be returned where the 

7729 index is ``q``, the columns are the columns of self, and the 

7730 values are the quantiles. 

7731 - If ``q`` is a float, a Series will be returned where the 

7732 index is the columns of self and the values are the quantiles. 

7733 

7734 See Also 

7735 -------- 

7736 core.window.Rolling.quantile: Rolling quantile. 

7737 numpy.percentile: Numpy function to compute the percentile. 

7738 

7739 Examples 

7740 -------- 

7741 >>> df = pd.DataFrame(np.array([[1, 1], [2, 10], [3, 100], [4, 100]]), 

7742 ... columns=['a', 'b']) 

7743 >>> df.quantile(.1) 

7744 a 1.3 

7745 b 3.7 

7746 Name: 0.1, dtype: float64 

7747 >>> df.quantile([.1, .5]) 

7748 a b 

7749 0.1 1.3 3.7 

7750 0.5 2.5 55.0 

7751 

7752 Specifying `numeric_only=False` will also compute the quantile of 

7753 datetime and timedelta data. 

7754 

7755 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A': [1, 2], 

7756 ... 'B': [pd.Timestamp('2010'), 

7757 ... pd.Timestamp('2011')], 

7758 ... 'C': [pd.Timedelta('1 days'), 

7759 ... pd.Timedelta('2 days')]}) 

7760 >>> df.quantile(0.5, numeric_only=False) 

7761 A 1.5 

7762 B 2010-07-02 12:00:00 

7763 C 1 days 12:00:00 

7764 Name: 0.5, dtype: object 

7765 """ 

7766 self._check_percentile(q) 

7767 

7768 data = self._get_numeric_data() if numeric_only else self 

7769 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

7770 is_transposed = axis == 1 

7771 

7772 if is_transposed: 

7773 data = data.T 

7774 

7775 result = data._data.quantile(qs=q, 

7776 axis=1, 

7777 interpolation=interpolation, 

7778 transposed=is_transposed) 

7779 

7780 if result.ndim == 2: 

7781 result = self._constructor(result) 

7782 else: 

7783 result = self._constructor_sliced(result, name=q) 

7784 

7785 if is_transposed: 

7786 result = result.T 

7787 

7788 return result

7790 def to_timestamp(self, freq=None, how='start', axis=0, copy=True): 

7791 """ 

7792 Cast to DatetimeIndex of timestamps, at *beginning* of period. 

7793 

7794 Parameters 

7795 ---------- 

7796 freq : string, default frequency of PeriodIndex 

7797 Desired frequency 

7798 how : {'s', 'e', 'start', 'end'} 

7799 Convention for converting period to timestamp; start of period 

7800 vs. end 

7801 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0 

7802 The axis to convert (the index by default) 

7803 copy : boolean, default True 

7804 If false then underlying input data is not copied 

7805 

7806 Returns 

7807 ------- 

7808 df : DataFrame with DatetimeIndex 

7809 """ 

7810 new_data = self._data 

7811 if copy: 

7812 new_data = new_data.copy() 

7813 

7814 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

7815 if axis == 0: 

7816 new_data.set_axis(1, self.index.to_timestamp(freq=freq, how=how)) 

7817 elif axis == 1: 

7818 new_data.set_axis(0, self.columns.to_timestamp(freq=freq, how=how)) 

7819 else: # pragma: no cover 

7820 raise AssertionError('Axis must be 0 or 1. Got {ax!s}'.format( 

7821 ax=axis)) 

7822 

7823 return self._constructor(new_data)

7825 def to_period(self, freq=None, axis=0, copy=True): 

7826 """ 

7827 Convert DataFrame from DatetimeIndex to PeriodIndex with desired 

7828 frequency (inferred from index if not passed). 

7829 

7830 Parameters 

7831 ---------- 

7832 freq : string, default 

7833 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0 

7834 The axis to convert (the index by default) 

7835 copy : boolean, default True 

7836 If False then underlying input data is not copied 

7837 

7838 Returns 

7839 ------- 

7840 ts : TimeSeries with PeriodIndex 

7841 """ 

7842 new_data = self._data 

7843 if copy: 

7844 new_data = new_data.copy() 

7845 

7846 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

7847 if axis == 0: 

7848 new_data.set_axis(1, self.index.to_period(freq=freq)) 

7849 elif axis == 1: 

7850 new_data.set_axis(0, self.columns.to_period(freq=freq)) 

7851 else: # pragma: no cover 

7852 raise AssertionError('Axis must be 0 or 1. Got {ax!s}'.format( 

7853 ax=axis)) 

7854 

7855 return self._constructor(new_data)

7857 def isin(self, values): 

7858 """ 

7859 Whether each element in the DataFrame is contained in values. 

7860 

7861 Parameters 

7862 ---------- 

7863 values : iterable, Series, DataFrame or dict 

7864 The result will only be true at a location if all the 

7865 labels match. If `values` is a Series, that's the index. If 

7866 `values` is a dict, the keys must be the column names, 

7867 which must match. If `values` is a DataFrame, 

7868 then both the index and column labels must match. 

7869 

7870 Returns 

7871 ------- 

7872 DataFrame 

7873 DataFrame of booleans showing whether each element in the DataFrame 

7874 is contained in values. 

7875 

7876 See Also 

7877 -------- 

7878 DataFrame.eq: Equality test for DataFrame. 

7879 Series.isin: Equivalent method on Series. 

7880 Series.str.contains: Test if pattern or regex is contained within a 

7881 string of a Series or Index. 

7882 

7883 Examples 

7884 -------- 

7885 

7886 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'num_legs': [2, 4], 'num_wings': [2, 0]}, 

7887 ... index=['falcon', 'dog']) 

7888 >>> df 

7889 num_legs num_wings 

7890 falcon 2 2 

7891 dog 4 0 

7892 

7893 When ``values`` is a list check whether every value in the DataFrame 

7894 is present in the list (which animals have 0 or 2 legs or wings) 

7895 

7896 >>> df.isin([0, 2]) 

7897 num_legs num_wings 

7898 falcon True True 

7899 dog False True 

7900 

7901 When ``values`` is a dict, we can pass values to check for each 

7902 column separately: 

7903 

7904 >>> df.isin({'num_wings': [0, 3]}) 

7905 num_legs num_wings 

7906 falcon False False 

7907 dog False True 

7908 

7909 When ``values`` is a Series or DataFrame the index and column must 

7910 match. Note that 'falcon' does not match based on the number of legs 

7911 in df2. 

7912 

7913 >>> other = pd.DataFrame({'num_legs': [8, 2],'num_wings': [0, 2]}, 

7914 ... index=['spider', 'falcon']) 

7915 >>> df.isin(other) 

7916 num_legs num_wings 

7917 falcon True True 

7918 dog False False 

7919 """ 

7920 if isinstance(values, dict): 

7921 from pandas.core.reshape.concat import concat 

7922 values = collections.defaultdict(list, values) 

7923 return concat((self.iloc[:, [i]].isin(values[col]) 

7924 for i, col in enumerate(self.columns)), axis=1) 

7925 elif isinstance(values, Series): 

7926 if not values.index.is_unique: 

7927 raise ValueError("cannot compute isin with " 

7928 "a duplicate axis.") 

7929 return self.eq(values.reindex_like(self), axis='index') 

7930 elif isinstance(values, DataFrame): 

7931 if not (values.columns.is_unique and values.index.is_unique): 

7932 raise ValueError("cannot compute isin with " 

7933 "a duplicate axis.") 

7934 return self.eq(values.reindex_like(self)) 

7935 else: 

7936 if not is_list_like(values): 

7937 raise TypeError("only list-like or dict-like objects are " 

7938 "allowed to be passed to DataFrame.isin(), " 

7939 "you passed a " 

7940 "{0!r}".format(type(values).__name__)) 

7941 return DataFrame( 

7942 algorithms.isin(self.values.ravel(), 

7943 values).reshape(self.shape), self.index, 

7944 self.columns)

7965def _from_nested_dict(data): 

7966 # TODO: this should be seriously cythonized 

7967 new_data = OrderedDict() 

7968 for index, s in compat.iteritems(data): 

7969 for col, v in compat.iteritems(s):
